I refused a contract.

00:52:49.490 --> 00:52:53.410
I thought that, if I wasn't
doing the job, I shouldn't be

00:52:53.410 --> 00:52:55.070
forced to stay in the company.

00:52:55.070 --> 00:52:58.380
They should have the right
to have a new CEO,

00:52:58.380 --> 00:53:00.530
so I turned it down.

00:53:00.530 --> 00:53:02.450
PROFESSOR ROBERT SHILLER: Is
that because the contract

00:53:02.450 --> 00:53:04.370
couldn't be explicit?

00:53:04.370 --> 00:53:05.700
MAURICE ''HANK'' GREENBERG:
Well, no.

00:53:05.700 --> 00:53:08.870
Say, that, if you have a
five-year contract, at the end

00:53:08.870 --> 00:53:11.980
of three years, if the company's
not doing well, why

00:53:11.980 --> 00:53:14.900
should the company be
forced to keep you

00:53:14.900 --> 00:53:16.150
for two more years?

00:53:28.080 --> 00:53:29.710
If you don't ask me
a question, I'll

00:53:29.710 --> 00:53:30.960
ask you some questions.

00:53:33.620 --> 00:53:43.976
STUDENT: I guess, this is more
of a personal question.

00:53:43.976 --> 00:53:45.654
I was wondering what --

00:53:45.654 --> 00:53:49.566
so, we're all in school, and
we don't have jobs yet.

00:53:49.566 --> 00:53:52.030
And so, in thinking about
careers, it's an important

00:53:52.030 --> 00:53:54.100
decision, so, I wondering
what made you

00:53:54.100 --> 00:53:55.150
really enjoy your job.

00:53:55.150 --> 00:53:56.690
Was it the success you had?

00:53:56.690 --> 00:53:59.640
Was it the day-to-day
activities?

00:53:59.640 --> 00:54:05.260
Was it the impact you made
on being part of AIG?

00:54:05.260 --> 00:54:05.510
MAURICE ''HANK'' GREENBERG:
Well, I

00:54:05.510 --> 00:54:06.500
think it's many things.

00:54:06.500 --> 00:54:08.900
You have to love what you
do, to begin with.

00:54:08.900 --> 00:54:11.070
And I love building.

00:54:11.070 --> 00:54:14.220
And I loved working with the
group of people that we had.

00:54:14.220 --> 00:54:17.260
It was a very close group.

00:54:17.260 --> 00:54:21.370
And it's a lot of fun opening
new markets, and beating our

00:54:21.370 --> 00:54:22.980
competitors.

00:54:22.980 --> 00:54:25.830
It was a very satisfying
experience.

00:54:25.830 --> 00:54:27.940
And you have to love it.

00:54:27.940 --> 00:54:31.210
The other thing I would say,
you need a lot of energy.

00:54:31.210 --> 00:54:35.710
You have to want -- you know,
work should not be viewed as,

00:54:35.710 --> 00:54:39.610
say, from nine to five.

00:54:39.610 --> 00:54:42.130
You work as long as you have to
because you love doing it.

00:54:55.078 --> 00:54:58.580
STUDENT: It also kind of reminds
me of Bear Stearns,

00:54:58.580 --> 00:55:03.076
and another very experienced
chairman, Ace Greenberg, kind

00:55:03.076 --> 00:55:04.820
of warning his board--

00:55:04.820 --> 00:55:07.013
MAURICE ''HANK'' GREENBERG:
I'm not hearing you.

00:55:07.013 --> 00:55:08.897
STUDENT: This is on?

00:55:08.897 --> 00:55:12.200
Like, AIG, the story of AIG
really reminds me of Bear

00:55:12.200 --> 00:55:12.697
Stearns' fall.

00:55:12.697 --> 00:55:16.156
And of a really experienced
board member pointing out that

00:55:16.156 --> 00:55:18.920
what the company was
doing wasn't great.

00:55:18.920 --> 00:55:23.980
So, can you talk to, I guess,
the idea of having experience

00:55:23.980 --> 00:55:27.570
in this field, and the fact that
companies were kind of --

00:55:27.570 --> 00:55:30.560
boards weren't working, was
also a core problem of the

00:55:30.560 --> 00:55:31.420
financial crisis.

00:55:31.420 --> 00:55:34.274
So, can you tell me a little
bit more about that and how

00:55:34.274 --> 00:55:36.570
you felt afterwards?

