MAURICE ''HANK'' GREENBERG:
I didn't quite hear that.

00:55:38.140 --> 00:55:39.540
Did you hear?

00:55:39.540 --> 00:55:39.910
PROFESSOR ROBERT
SHILLER: Boards

00:55:39.910 --> 00:55:43.390
were not working properly.

00:55:43.390 --> 00:55:44.550
MAURICE ''HANK'' GREENBERG:
Boards were not working

00:55:44.550 --> 00:55:46.535
properly is absolutely right.

00:55:49.720 --> 00:55:53.620
There was a lead director
in the company --

00:55:53.620 --> 00:55:57.210
if you go back through the
history of AIG, we had some

00:55:57.210 --> 00:56:00.950
outstanding people
on the board.

00:56:00.950 --> 00:56:04.410
Over a period of time, some
retire, some die.

00:56:04.410 --> 00:56:06.470
But we had a pretty
good board.

00:56:06.470 --> 00:56:09.850
Carla Hills, for example, was
on the board, and she was an

00:56:09.850 --> 00:56:11.460
outstanding director.

00:56:11.460 --> 00:56:19.390
She had been in the cabinet of
George Bush, the first. She

00:56:19.390 --> 00:56:22.850
was a terrific director.

00:56:22.850 --> 00:56:24.620
Bill Cohen, who had
been secretary of

00:56:24.620 --> 00:56:28.920
defense, was a director.

00:56:28.920 --> 00:56:33.320
Dick Holbrooke, who recently
died, was a director.

00:56:33.320 --> 00:56:36.020
So, we have had some
good directors.

00:56:36.020 --> 00:56:39.630
On the other hand, when
Spitzer threatened the

00:56:39.630 --> 00:56:44.600
company, many of them
just folded.

00:56:44.600 --> 00:56:49.270
Not Carla Hills and not Bill
Cohen, but many others.

00:56:49.270 --> 00:56:53.350
And you don't know, how people
are going to respond until

00:56:53.350 --> 00:56:57.730
they're confronted
with an issue.

00:56:57.730 --> 00:57:00.270
But there's no question that
the board failed, in my

00:57:00.270 --> 00:57:03.730
judgment, to recognize what was
happening after I left.

00:57:13.078 --> 00:57:15.538
STUDENT: So, China has recently
been experiencing

00:57:15.538 --> 00:57:16.522
rapid growth.

00:57:16.522 --> 00:57:19.551
How do you think their growth,
the change toward a

00:57:19.551 --> 00:57:20.778
consumption model,
will change the

00:57:20.778 --> 00:57:24.372
insurance industry in China?

00:57:24.372 --> 00:57:26.136
PROFESSOR ROBERT SHILLER: China,
you're saying, has been

00:57:26.136 --> 00:57:26.840
growing rapidly.

00:57:26.840 --> 00:57:27.840
MAURICE ''HANK'' GREENBERG:
What is?

00:57:27.840 --> 00:57:29.031
STUDENT: How will
that change the

00:57:29.031 --> 00:57:31.655
insurance industry in China?

00:57:31.655 --> 00:57:33.812
PROFESSOR ROBERT SHILLER: The
insurance industry in China,

00:57:33.812 --> 00:57:39.260
how is it changing with
their rapid growth?

00:57:39.260 --> 00:57:40.550
MAURICE ''HANK'' GREENBERG:
It's changed dramatically.

00:57:40.550 --> 00:57:44.780
The largest insurance company in
the world today, by market

00:57:44.780 --> 00:57:48.710
value, is China Life.

00:57:48.710 --> 00:57:53.040
Amazing growth in China,
and you expected it.

00:57:53.040 --> 00:57:56.090
China has passed the United
States in the number of

00:57:56.090 --> 00:57:58.540
automobiles being sold a year.

00:57:58.540 --> 00:58:01.430
They all have to be insured.

00:58:01.430 --> 00:58:04.820
So, the growth in the insurance
industry in China is

00:58:04.820 --> 00:58:06.070
very rapid.

00:58:10.570 --> 00:58:15.990
Very immature in many ways in
understanding risk, but

00:58:15.990 --> 00:58:16.900
that'll change.

00:58:16.900 --> 00:58:19.280
They've come a long ways.

00:58:19.280 --> 00:58:23.260
When I first went to China,
and we entered our life

00:58:23.260 --> 00:58:27.360
company, the life insurance
industry in

00:58:27.360 --> 00:58:29.700
China was very small.

00:58:29.700 --> 00:58:32.480
And they didn't have agents
selling life insurance.

00:58:32.480 --> 00:58:37.350
They had their employees
selling life insurance.

00:58:37.350 --> 00:58:43.020
So, if an employee sold
something, he would get paid,

00:58:43.020 --> 00:58:46.110
and he'd get paid whether
he sold or not.

00:58:46.110 --> 00:58:48.340
So, they had a fixed expense.

00:58:48.340 --> 00:58:53.660
We introduced an agency system
in China, and recruited

00:58:53.660 --> 00:58:56.480
thousands of agents.

00:58:56.480 --> 00:58:58.780
And they got commissions,
if they sold something.

00:58:58.780 --> 00:59:02.350
If they didn't sell, they
didn't get a commission.

00:59:02.350 --> 00:59:05.760
The Chinese companies quickly
adapted to our system.

00:59:05.760 --> 00:59:08.320
So, you can say that we created
millions and millions

00:59:08.320 --> 00:59:09.810
of jobs in China.

00:59:14.220 --> 00:59:15.020
STUDENT: Thank you.

00:59:15.020 --> 00:59:18.560
I'm just wondering what you do
you think of Chartis and

00:59:18.560 --> 00:59:21.870
SunAmerica, currently
sub-businesses, and how you

00:59:21.870 --> 00:59:26.860
would evaluate Robert Benmosche
as the current CEO.

00:59:26.860 --> 00:59:27.990
MAURICE ''HANK'' GREENBERG:
Look, I've known Bob Benmosche

00:59:27.990 --> 00:59:32.860
for 15, 20 years, and
he's a decent man.

00:59:32.860 --> 00:59:34.360
He's a good man.

00:59:34.360 --> 00:59:39.140
And he's, I think, a
pretty good leader.

00:59:39.140 --> 00:59:42.360
He has very little experience
internationally, and his

00:59:42.360 --> 00:59:46.300
experience has been in the life
insurance sector, not in

00:59:46.300 --> 00:59:48.780
the non-life sector.

00:59:48.780 --> 00:59:53.990
One of the largest components of
AIG is the non-life sector,

00:59:53.990 --> 01:00:00.090
so he's got a hard job
in front of him.

01:00:00.090 --> 01:00:04.110
Also, the most valuable
assets have been sold.

01:00:04.110 --> 01:00:10.580
The AIA, which is the company
that's entered in China, that

01:00:10.580 --> 01:00:15.740
AIG owns 100% of, they
sold that, which I

01:00:15.740 --> 01:00:16.865
wouldn't have done.

01:00:16.865 --> 01:00:21.910
And they sold American Life
to Metropolitan Life.

01:00:21.910 --> 01:00:25.780
That company does business in 55
countries around the world.

01:00:25.780 --> 01:00:27.560
You can't replicate that.

01:00:27.560 --> 01:00:29.280
I wouldn't have sold that.

01:00:29.280 --> 01:00:34.050
So, AIG is a shadow of
what it was before.

01:00:34.050 --> 01:00:36.970
Benmosche's got a tough job.

01:00:36.970 --> 01:00:40.360
He doesn't know the non-life
business very well.

01:00:40.360 --> 01:00:44.440
And the culture of the
company is gone.

01:00:44.440 --> 01:00:47.610
Most of the people who worked
there, who were some of the

01:00:47.610 --> 01:00:49.160
better people, have left.

01:00:51.930 --> 01:00:57.060
Many have come to me, and are
working in C.V. Starr &amp; Co.,

01:00:57.060 --> 01:00:59.505
and in our agencies and our
insurance companies.

01:01:02.628 --> 01:01:05.390
It's going to be a tough job,
but he's a good man.

01:01:05.390 --> 01:01:08.750
I like him.

01:01:08.750 --> 01:01:10.160
STUDENT: Good morning.

01:01:10.160 --> 01:01:13.660
During your speech, you get to
the destructive power of

01:01:13.660 --> 01:01:15.420
credit default swaps.

01:01:15.420 --> 01:01:18.228
And what I find interesting is,
different countries have

01:01:18.228 --> 01:01:19.570
taken a very different
approach.

01:01:19.570 --> 01:01:22.390
Some European countries have
absolutely banned credit

01:01:22.390 --> 01:01:23.300
default swaps.

01:01:23.300 --> 01:01:25.570
China, most notably, introduced
them in the market

01:01:25.570 --> 01:01:28.720
recently, but put a cap
on the value with

01:01:28.720 --> 01:01:30.410
the underlying amount.

01:01:30.410 --> 01:01:33.413
So my question really is, what
sort of regulation do you

01:01:33.413 --> 01:01:36.480
think would work well, both
at a national level and,

01:01:36.480 --> 01:01:39.560
possibly, the international
level?

01:01:39.560 --> 01:01:41.280
MAURICE ''HANK'' GREENBERG:
That's a good question.

01:01:41.280 --> 01:01:43.400
I would do at least
two things.

01:01:43.400 --> 01:01:47.810
First, I would go back to where
a credit default swap

01:01:47.810 --> 01:01:51.530
would only respond if the
underlying instrument, that it

01:01:51.530 --> 01:01:55.960
is supposedly insuring,
defaults.

01:01:55.960 --> 01:01:59.230
In other words, I would not
respond to just a reduction in

01:01:59.230 --> 01:02:06.480
value, because if you look at
all those CDOs, that the

01:02:06.480 --> 01:02:09.750
credit default swaps were
covering, most of those have

01:02:09.750 --> 01:02:12.050
recovered in value.

01:02:12.050 --> 01:02:16.750
OK, so that there was a
temporary reduction in value,

01:02:16.750 --> 01:02:19.140
but they didn't default.

01:02:19.140 --> 01:02:22.540
And so, what it led
to was unnecessary

01:02:22.540 --> 01:02:24.150
chaos in the market.

01:02:24.150 --> 01:02:29.400
The second thing, I would have
is an exchange, where you get

01:02:29.400 --> 01:02:31.760
price discovery.

01:02:31.760 --> 01:02:34.785
Without price discovery, you're
back where you were,

01:02:34.785 --> 01:02:36.840
and so you have to have that.

01:02:36.840 --> 01:02:39.270
And you'd have to
put up reserves.

01:02:39.270 --> 01:02:41.950
If I was going to issue credit
default swaps, you ought to

01:02:41.950 --> 01:02:42.660
reserve it.

01:02:42.660 --> 01:02:45.370
If it's going to be an insurance
instrument, treat it

01:02:45.370 --> 01:02:47.270
like an insurance instrument.

01:02:47.270 --> 01:02:51.980
And make the underlying company,
who's issuing them,

01:02:51.980 --> 01:02:53.230
put up reserves.

01:02:57.860 --> 01:03:02.300
STUDENT: It can be a bit
intimidating sometimes to

01:03:02.300 --> 01:03:04.840
hear, or learn, or read about
the insurance industry because

01:03:04.840 --> 01:03:07.590
of the regulation, and the
billions and billions of

01:03:07.590 --> 01:03:09.340
dollars that are always
involved, et

01:03:09.340 --> 01:03:11.370
cetera, as a student.

01:03:11.370 --> 01:03:13.490
But I'm wondering, in addition
to what you're doing yourself

01:03:13.490 --> 01:03:19.310
now, with C.V. Starr, what
opportunities do you see for

01:03:19.310 --> 01:03:21.830
entrepreneurship in
the insurance

01:03:21.830 --> 01:03:24.170
industry today, if any.

01:03:24.170 --> 01:03:24.770
MAURICE ''HANK'' GREENBERG:
Well, I think there's

01:03:24.770 --> 01:03:28.680
tremendous opportunity for
being an entrepreneur.

01:03:28.680 --> 01:03:33.100
You know, you're living in a
changing world, changing

01:03:33.100 --> 01:03:36.080
economies, new products
are being invented and

01:03:36.080 --> 01:03:38.940
developed every day.

01:03:38.940 --> 01:03:41.110
And investments are going
on in different

01:03:41.110 --> 01:03:42.310
parts of the world.

01:03:42.310 --> 01:03:44.440
All of that needs insurance.

01:03:44.440 --> 01:03:47.510
And so, there's great
opportunity to be creative in

01:03:47.510 --> 01:03:50.950
the insurance industry, and
differentiate yourself from

01:03:50.950 --> 01:03:52.440
everybody else.

01:03:52.440 --> 01:03:54.030
I'm about to do a joint venture

01:03:54.030 --> 01:03:56.490
insurance company in China.

01:03:56.490 --> 01:03:59.080
The one we're doing a joint
venture with, a very

01:03:59.080 --> 01:04:01.440
traditional company.

01:04:01.440 --> 01:04:04.750
We will change that in
less than a year

01:04:04.750 --> 01:04:07.810
into something different.

01:04:07.810 --> 01:04:10.450
And that's exciting
to do that.

01:04:10.450 --> 01:04:11.960
So, I'm looking forward to it.

01:04:34.670 --> 01:04:36.480
STUDENT: Hi.

01:04:36.480 --> 01:04:37.370
Do you think that --

01:04:37.370 --> 01:04:39.663
I mean, with the recent
financial crisis, we've seen a

01:04:39.663 --> 01:04:42.890
lot of government intervention
and interaction through the

01:04:42.890 --> 01:04:43.610
private world.

01:04:43.610 --> 01:04:46.595
And I was wondering, do you
think that the government

01:04:46.595 --> 01:04:49.840
should have any role, other than
just keeping things fair?

01:04:49.840 --> 01:04:52.042
Do you think they should
intervene, when these

01:04:52.042 --> 01:04:53.247
companies are having
big issues, like

01:04:53.247 --> 01:04:55.900
what happened to AIG?

01:04:55.900 --> 01:04:56.410
MAURICE ''HANK'' GREENBERG:
Do I think

01:04:56.410 --> 01:04:57.790
government should intervene?

01:04:57.790 --> 01:05:00.630
I think that --

01:05:00.630 --> 01:05:02.015
the least amount that's
necessary.

01:05:04.970 --> 01:05:07.580
I think, if you're asking the
question of ''too big to

01:05:07.580 --> 01:05:11.950
fail'', I think there are some
institutions that probably

01:05:11.950 --> 01:05:15.170
would cause chaos
if they failed.

01:05:15.170 --> 01:05:21.230
But I would make that very,
very few and far between.

01:05:21.230 --> 01:05:27.540
What troubles me is, what
happened in this recession in

01:05:27.540 --> 01:05:29.160
government intervention.

01:05:29.160 --> 01:05:31.690
They picked and chose who
they wanted to save

01:05:31.690 --> 01:05:33.410
and who they didn't.

01:05:33.410 --> 01:05:35.885
It wasn't even-handed.

01:05:35.885 --> 01:05:41.710
It was done with the intent to
save some and not others.

01:05:41.710 --> 01:05:43.990
The real story of what
happened has not

01:05:43.990 --> 01:05:47.800
been printed yet.

01:05:47.800 --> 01:05:51.485
After all, it's very common
knowledge that Paulson, who

01:05:51.485 --> 01:05:54.740
was then Treasury Secretary,
was surrounded by Goldman

01:05:54.740 --> 01:05:57.500
Sachs people.

01:05:57.500 --> 01:05:58.640
I'm not making that up.

01:05:58.640 --> 01:06:02.930
That happens to be a fact.

01:06:02.930 --> 01:06:09.360
And so, how objective were
they in what they were

01:06:09.360 --> 01:06:13.510
deciding to do and not to?

01:06:13.510 --> 01:06:16.140
I think that there are times
government has to intervene,

01:06:16.140 --> 01:06:21.190
but I happen to believe in the
private sector, in the ability

01:06:21.190 --> 01:06:24.900
of Americans to create
jobs and businesses.

01:06:24.900 --> 01:06:26.410
And government should
be small.

01:06:26.410 --> 01:06:29.020
Government created jobs
and not the best jobs.

01:06:29.020 --> 01:06:33.000
Private sector jobs are the
best jobs, in my judgment.

01:06:52.840 --> 01:06:54.080
STUDENT: Thank you.

01:06:54.080 --> 01:06:56.550
What role do you think that
banks should play in the

01:06:56.550 --> 01:06:58.785
future to avoid a
similar crisis?

01:06:58.785 --> 01:07:02.130
And do you think that there
needs to be a different sense

01:07:02.130 --> 01:07:04.260
of what risk is?

01:07:04.260 --> 01:07:06.460
MAURICE ''HANK'' GREENBERG:
What was the last part?

01:07:06.460 --> 01:07:07.802
STUDENT: What kind
of role should

01:07:07.802 --> 01:07:09.800
banks play in the future?

01:07:09.800 --> 01:07:11.584
And do you think that there
needs to be a different

01:07:11.584 --> 01:07:13.600
definition of what risk is?

01:07:13.600 --> 01:07:15.030
MAURICE ''HANK'' GREENBERG:
Of what risk is?

01:07:15.030 --> 01:07:15.500
STUDENT: Risk.

01:07:15.500 --> 01:07:18.580
MAURICE ''HANK'' GREENBERG:
Yeah, OK.

01:07:18.580 --> 01:07:20.820
When you say banks, you have
to differentiate between

01:07:20.820 --> 01:07:23.670
commercial banks and
investment banks.

01:07:23.670 --> 01:07:28.730
Look, I think that the
Dodd-Frank bill, that has been

01:07:28.730 --> 01:07:34.180
passed, comes up with a whole
new set of regulations.

01:07:34.180 --> 01:07:35.930
Let me touch on that
in a minute.

01:07:35.930 --> 01:07:45.580
And will banks use their own
capital to do transactions

01:07:45.580 --> 01:07:49.495
that put the whole institution
at risk?

01:07:49.495 --> 01:07:52.890
It probably will not
be the way it was.

01:07:52.890 --> 01:07:58.290
I think the Volcker Rule, which
would limit the amount

01:07:58.290 --> 01:08:01.200
of individual transactions
that might

01:08:01.200 --> 01:08:02.960
endanger the bank --

01:08:02.960 --> 01:08:04.300
they are going to be limited.

01:08:04.300 --> 01:08:08.130
It'd have to use an off-balance
sheet approach, so

01:08:08.130 --> 01:08:11.290
that that doesn't pollute
the rest of the bank.

01:08:11.290 --> 01:08:15.180
Investment banks, for example,
that may have done

01:08:15.180 --> 01:08:20.060
transactions, that bet against
their own clients, I think

01:08:20.060 --> 01:08:21.439
should be outlawed.

01:08:21.439 --> 01:08:25.939
If an investment bank is selling
me, say, invest in the

01:08:25.939 --> 01:08:31.330
XYZ CDO, and then they take a
position against that, it

01:08:31.330 --> 01:08:34.210
seems to me that
that's immoral.

01:08:34.210 --> 01:08:37.189
And that should not
be permitted.

01:08:37.189 --> 01:08:42.790
Now, the Dodd-Frank bill was
enacted, before they even had

01:08:42.790 --> 01:08:46.479
any of the response of all
the investigations

01:08:46.479 --> 01:08:47.870
that were going on.

01:08:47.870 --> 01:08:51.410
It seems to me, they should have
waited and hear what the

01:08:51.410 --> 01:08:54.189
investigators had come
up with, before they

01:08:54.189 --> 01:08:57.109
passed a new law.

01:08:57.109 --> 01:09:03.729
Now, Congress has to provide for
the financing of all these

01:09:03.729 --> 01:09:07.540
new regulators that are going
to be created under the

01:09:07.540 --> 01:09:08.670
Dodd-Frank bill.

01:09:08.670 --> 01:09:11.100
And I'm not sure that's
going to happen.

01:09:11.100 --> 01:09:13.850
I'm not so sure that all
of them are necessary.

01:09:13.850 --> 01:09:15.700
What we need are better
regulators, not more

01:09:15.700 --> 01:09:16.990
regulation.

01:09:16.990 --> 01:09:18.279
We had plenty of regulation.

01:09:18.279 --> 01:09:20.189
If they had enforced the
regulations that were in

01:09:20.189 --> 01:09:23.300
existence, we would have avoided
a great deal, if not

01:09:23.300 --> 01:09:24.550
all, of what took place.

01:09:40.580 --> 01:09:41.350
STUDENT: Hi.

01:09:41.350 --> 01:09:44.640
You mentioned earlier about how
AIG attracted and retained

01:09:44.640 --> 01:09:47.540
the best people in the business,
and that's how they

01:09:47.540 --> 01:09:50.140
grew, because of the strong
culture there.

01:09:50.140 --> 01:09:53.790
But if you're starting a new
company, or even entering in a

01:09:53.790 --> 01:09:56.785
management position at a current
company, how do you go

01:09:56.785 --> 01:09:59.250
about building that type
of culture that

01:09:59.250 --> 01:10:00.807
just fosters growth?

01:10:00.807 --> 01:10:03.192
PROFESSOR ROBERT SHILLER: How do
you build the culture that

01:10:03.192 --> 01:10:05.100
you have talked about?

01:10:05.100 --> 01:10:06.455
MAURICE ''HANK'' GREENBERG: The
culture starts at the top.

01:10:09.240 --> 01:10:10.620
It's got to start with the

01:10:10.620 --> 01:10:13.050
individual running the company.

01:10:13.050 --> 01:10:17.480
The same thing, as I say,
in risk management.

01:10:17.480 --> 01:10:21.910
The CEO is the top risk manager
in the company.

01:10:21.910 --> 01:10:23.580
You have other people
involved, but

01:10:23.580 --> 01:10:24.770
you're the risk manager.

01:10:24.770 --> 01:10:26.950
You decide, how much risk
you really want to take.

01:10:26.950 --> 01:10:29.410
And the same thing is
true in culture.

01:10:29.410 --> 01:10:32.540
You build a culture based upon
your performance, what you

01:10:32.540 --> 01:10:36.230
stand for, what you believe in,
and you surround yourself

01:10:36.230 --> 01:10:38.630
with people who share
those beliefs.

01:10:38.630 --> 01:10:41.610
If they don't, they'll
feel out of step.

01:10:45.610 --> 01:10:46.465
PROFESSOR ROBERT SHILLER:
All right.

01:10:46.465 --> 01:10:48.272
Thank you very much.

01:10:48.272 --> 01:10:50.006
[APPLAUSE]

